Q25: As a physician we are facing new and unknown threats. Difficult to balance the protection measures against virus spread vs economic impact in the whole society. Measures have to be taken based on previous experiences and daily information. But experiences in other countries not always reflect the reality for the new comers, and information is not completely trustable due to the lack of testing. In one hand we have the chaotic situation inside hospitals and ICUs, with health personnel exposed to a death risk without proper protection. On the other, the great majority of the population healthy and inside a safe environment looking ahead and worried about their future. Nobody is wrong. It is a matter or perspective. As a health care provider, my view is - first let’s save as many lives as we can, lowering the curve and offering the possibility of being treated for all the severe cases. Observe how society and infection dissemination evolves. Program to reduce limitations as quickly as possible, starting with lower risk groups. Observe if there is a second hit. Release more groups. Let the economy move. Observe. Release more. Second wave will come when children start to go to school, they will get mild infection but will bring it home and we will see numbers rise again. While all this happen, as a doctor, we will still have to support our patients, our families and our medical societies, trying to guess what is the best next step. Not easy, but we cannot stop.
